    ErrorVariable                                                              {ev}
    WarningVariable                                                            {wv}
    OutVariable                                                                {ov}
    OutBuffer                                                                  {ob}
    PipelineVariable                                                           {pv}

```

It seems you could add a parameterset that includes all of the Curl parameters, and since those parameters are currently not even valid for the command, you could simply check $PSCmdlet.ParameterSetName to see if they are passing parameters for the real command, then run the Get-Command -all to resolve it.

@jpsnover
Seems like an approach like "Remove-All-Aliases-That-Are-Linux-Commands" makes sense, but I feel it needs to be larger in scope than the working name would suggest.  This issue is symptomatic of a larger concern about being able to make improvements to PowerShell without breaking backward compatibility _in general_, not just limited to aliases or per-platform issues.

I'd suggest that a script should be able to declare for which version of PowerShell it was intended.  That a `Use-Version 4` command or metadata declaration at the top of a script would opt you into a runtime environment tailored for that version, and that runtime environment then need not necessarily be backward compatible; and that this could impact more than just aliases but even extending to parsing changes or other behavioral changes, similar to how Perl's `use v5.10;` statement is used to opt into possibly breaking features.

@drysart I'm not sure if you realize be there is already a "requires"  functionality available:
https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hh847765.aspx

It's certainly a little different than what you've described, in that if you require version 5 for instance, the script simply won't run on v4 or below.

I have another idea that can keep backward compatibility + fix the problem.
do something that "intelligently" check if the user is trying to run the wget/curl(.exe) OR Microsft version of "incomatible alias wget/curl".

This can be done via testing argument. (easy since Microsoft didnt made the alias compatible)

**Rough code:**

```
alias curl="intelligent-fix-curl"

# to keep track of what the user is interested in
webrequest-was-invoked-last-time = false

def intelligent-fix-curl() {
    invoke-webrequest = false

    if (user-provided-no-argument) {
        invoke-webrequest = webrequest-was-invoked-last-time
    } else if (user-probebly-providing-webrequest-style-argument) {
        invoke-webrequest = true
    }

    webrequest-was-invoked-last-time = invoke-webrequest

    if (invoke-webrequest) {
        PRINT "WARNING: alias curl=Invoke-WebRequest has been depriciated"
        CALL Invoke-WebRequest with ARGUMENTS
    } else {
        CALL curl.exe with ARGUMENT
    }
}
```

**IMO**,
If something else exists before (in the case curl/wget), assume that user want the existing one.
desiging something that don't play cool (incomatible) with the exisiting community is seen frowning.
be it project name, be it utility name, be it anything. Please dont try to create confusion.

Also,
Instead some global option should have been provided (in the first place) if user explicitly allow such confusing alias.
We expect the user to take the final decision. 

